  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Non-obstructive coronary artery disease (NOCAD) frequently accounts for myocardial ischemia
      in women. Endothelial dysfunction is a pathogenic factor in coronary spastic angina (CSA).
      CSA is an important cause of NOCAD diagnosed invasively by coronary angiography (CAG).
      Digital reactive hyperemia peripheral arterial tonometry (RH-PAT) provides noninvasive
      evaluation of endothelial dysfunction. The investigators hypothesized that the fingertip
      RH-PAT could predict the presence of CSA in women.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
  <detailed_description>
    <textblock>
      Outline of methods:

      RH-PAT was measured in women with chest pain prior to CAG. Coronary spasm was diagnosed by
      intra-coronary acetylcholine (ACh) provocation test. Using Flow-Wire, we assessed coronary
      endothelial function by coronary blood flow increase in response to ACh (ACh-CBF) and
      coronary flow reserve was assessed by adenosine (Ad-CFR).
    </textblock>
  </detailed_description>
